A web user was placed in criminal detention for flinging abuse at citizens and cities in typhoon-affected Zhejiang Province, East China, according to a post released on Sunday by the Qinhuai district public security authority of Nanjing, East China's Jiangsu Province.The web user, surnamed Wang, 37, was reported on Saturday for the abuse in multiple posts in his Sina Weibo account, China's Twitter-like social media platform, and causing a negative influence online, according to the police's post.Qinhuai district police arrested Wang soon after receiving the report, and Wang has confessed. Wang is currently under criminal detention for defiance and affray, read the post.Police in Taizhou city of Zhejiang Province also reminded web users that the internet is not extrajudicial territory. With regard to online acts such as maliciously abusing, insulting, slandering and disturbing the public order, the public security authorities will investigate and punish perpetrators according to the law. It is hoped that all web users will obey the law and regulations, make rational remarks and jointly create a good cyber environment, according to a post on Taizhou police's Sina Weibo account.Huang Chao, a lawyer with the Jianqiao Yihua Law Firm based in Suzhou of Jiangsu, told the Global Times that Wang's criminal detention for defiance and affray is reasonable, and under this charge, Wang will face a maximum prison term of five years.According to China's Criminal Law, abusing and insulting others could constitute the crime of defiance and affray. Criminals that abuse others on the internet can receive sentences ranging from six months to five years, according to the previous 60 cases involving internet abuse that are open to the public, said Huang. 
